<TEXT>
salmon production is soaring at fish farms 
worldwide spurred in part by greater demand and buying power in 
japan an agriculture department report says 
worldwide salmon production is estimated up 75 percent from 
last year to over 300 million pounds the report said norway 
the top producer likely raised about 160 million pounds in 1988 
almost double 1987s output 
in the united states salmon farming or aquaculture is 
concentrated in washington oregon california and most recently 
maine last years production was around 85 million pounds but the 
us salmon figures for 1988 are not available yet 
large japanese demand and the strong value of the yen has boosted 
competition in world salmon markets the report said the heavy 
buying by japan has reduced the us supply of topquality salmon 
available to consumers forcing some restaurants to remove salmon 
from their menus 
a buying frenzy resulted from early reports of a small alaskan 
catch coupled with losses in the norwegian salmon crop because of a 
red tide infestation of a microorganism that reduces the oxygen 
level of the water so the fish suffocate the report said 
salmon farming makes up only a fraction of total us aquaculture 
production but some authorities believe the industry is poised for 
a major expansion perhaps doubling or tripling domestic output in a 
few years 
the report was prepared by economists mike dicks and david harvey 
of the departments economic research service who are the agencys 
chief aquaculture specialists 
harvey said in a telephone interview that the us salmon 
production figures are being studied and revised to get a more 
accurate picture of how much of the output goes into the commercial 
food supply 
also he said whether the current salmon boom continues will 
depend on many economic legal and consumer factors 
overall including food and nonfood fish shellfish and other 
aquatic products us aquacultural output rose by 20 percent in 
1987 to almost 750 million pounds worth 650 million 
the 1987 expansion was led by catfish crawfish and salmon with 
a combined production of more than 550 million pounds or about 73 
percent of the total catfish output was estimated at 370 million 
pounds crawfish 95 million pounds and salmon about 85 million 
pounds 
but the report said that expansion probably will slow to less 
than 10 percent a year in the next 10 years unless new technology 
and more resources become available 
a shortage of water supplies likely will impede expansion 
particularly in areas where production is already highly 
concentrated the report said where aquaculture is just 
beginning to develop limited management resources capital and 
industry infrastructure will constrain expansion 
with a slower growth and little increase expected in the 
commercial catch of wild fish americans probably will depend 
increasingly on imports which totaled 88 billion in 1987 
however the report added this could be modified by new technology 
growth of the commercial fishing fleet and shifts in consumer demand 
the report noted some of the new research and technology in the 
industry 
in maine research continues on lobster production and in 
canada scientists are working with the black cod a favorite in 
japan and the united states 
striped bass or rockfish were in short supply following a ban 
on their catch three years ago in the chesapeake bay the main 
production area the fish are now being produced in california and 
north carolina with production likely starting up next year in 
texas arizona mississippi and maryland 
oysters littleneck clams red fish and sturgeon are other 
species traditionally supplied from the wild catch that are now 
being farmed 
the development of genetically superior catfish and trout offers 
potential for expansion for example auburn university has crossed 
a commercial blue catfish with the channel catfish to produce a 
hybrid with a 40 percent greater growth rate and a high tolerance 
for lowoxygen water 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

