<TEXT>
here are some facts and figures about sri lanka 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
land sri lanka is an island of 25332 square miles about the 
size of west virginia off indias southern coast it was known as 
ceylon until 1972 and arab traders of long ago called it serendip 
or the land of pleasant surprises sri lanka means bountiful 
island in the sinhala language 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
people the breakdown of the islands 16 million population is 
75 percent sinhalese 18 percent tamil 7 percent moslem and a few 
descendants of european settlers the sinhalese who are 
predominantly buddhist and tamils most of whom are hindu came 
from india centuries ago across the narrow palk strait 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
history since ancient times the island was invaded by the 
armies of indian kings the portuguese colonized it in the 16th 
century the dutch ruled in the 17th century and the british were in 
control from about 1800 until independence in 1948 
battles between sinhalese and tamils are rooted in sri lankas 
history but the basis for the current civil war was laid by british 
encouragment of minority tamils in education and jobs under the 
divide and rule policy 
after independence the sinhalese tried to contain tamil 
influence a law passed in 1956 declared sinhala as the official 
language 
tamil riots began and resentment grew of sinhalese dominance in 
government the military and education the problem was excerbated 
by the religious difference the civil war began when tamil rebels 
killed 13 sri lankan soldiers in 1983 setting off riots in which 
more than 1000 tamil civilians were killed 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
economy before the ethnic war began sri lanka was a model 
third world developing country its economy grew an average of 7 
percent a year and tea exports spices and tourism were mainstays 
economic growth last year fell to less than 15 percent and tourism 
has dropped to a fraction of the 250000 people who visited annually 
in prewar years 
per capita income is about 380 a year 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881219-0039 </DOCNO>
