<TEXT>
the defense department is about to launch a new 
research effort to improve the definition or clarity of 
television screen pictures and in the process hopefully bolster the 
american tv manufacturing industry 
the department in a brief statement said its defense advanced 
research projects agency hoped in the next two to three weeks to 
solicit contract proposals in the areas of highdefinition 
lowcost display technology 
the pentagons primary goal is the development of an advanced 
but small tvtype screen or monitor that can display text 
characters or video signals with great clarity said spokeswoman jan 
bodanyi 
the monitors would be used inside new helicopters and airplanes 
training simulators and other types of vehicles and command centers 
the defense department also hopes however that by providing 
seed money for new research it can enlist electronic and 
semiconductor companies to fight japan for the lead in developing 
the next generation of tv sets for commercial use 
highdefinition television or hdtv offers the promise of 
sharper brighter and wider pictures that could match the quality of 
motion picture films japanese industry has developed an hdtv system 
and plans to begin marketing it in 1990 
a consortium of european firms also is thought to be ahead of 
american industry in exploring the new technology 
pentagon officials say they hope that by prodding research in the 
field of highdefinition monitors the government also can 
ultimately spur domestic manufacturing of semiconductors the 
electronic chips at the heart of computers 
the hdtv technology will require extensive use of semiconductors 
and that could provide the incentive needed by domestic companies to 
reenter the semiconductor market said one official who asked not 
to be identified 
the source added the zenith electronics corp which remains 
usowned is almost sure to be included in the darpa effort 
zenith already has asked for a 15 million contract to develop what 
it calls flat tension mask technology 
the flat tension mask resembles a conventional tv picture tube 
but has a flat face that is sharper and much more rugged which 
would make it attractive for battlefield use 
but this wont be a onecompany effort added the source 
the pentagon in its statement said darpa had been working in 
the arena of highdefinition monitors for years and where 
practical will conform to evolving commercial hdtv standards 
a technology base common to defense and commercial needs 
benefits dod as lower unit prices result from largescale 
production the statement added 
hdtv and computers share a common dependence on 
semiconductors dod has an interest in maintaining a robust us 
semiconductor industry so as to assure a domestic source of the most 
advanced microelectronic products 
the washington post first reported on the tv research project in 
monday editions 
