<TEXT>
an excited young andean condor flapped her 
wings and took off on her first flight as biologists freed three of 
the birds into the wild to pave the way for the eventual release of 
endangered california condors 
the three birds were the first of up to 17 andean condors 
donated by various zoos where they were born that will be freed by 
late 1989 so scientists can test the techniques they hope to use 
when they release california condors which are north americas 
largest birds with 9foot wingspans 
only 28 endangered california condors remain alive all in zoos 
in los angeles and san diego officials are trying to get the 
carrioneating vultures to breed in captivity in hopes of starting 
to reintroduce them into the wild in five to 10 years 
the release of the first three andean birds started last friday 
night in a wet and snowy hopper mountain national wildlife refuge 
about 50 miles northwest of downtown los angeles the three birds 
living in a netcovered enclosure set into rocks were placed in a 
roost box while scientists removed the netting us fish and 
