<TEXT>
john duda who helped his seminole county 
family build one of the nations largest agricultural empires has 
died after a long illness he was 84 
duda who died saturday worked behind the scenes to design 
special farming irrigation and packing equipment that is now widely 
used in farming on organic soils 
what a duda amp sons began as a 10acre farm near oviedo 
mushroomed into a farming giant from florida to california and 
australia today the company is diversified into vegetables citrus 
sugar cane sod foliage cattle and real estate development 
as the son of andrew duda sr the family patriarch who emigrated 
from czechoslovakia with his wife and children in 1912 john duda 
and his brothers andrew jr and ferdinand learned about farming 
from the land they had no formal training or high school education 
born in velcice czechoslovakia john duda joined the family 
business in 1926 he retired as corporate vice president in 1976 and 
served on the duda board of directors until january of this year 
they really exemplify a ragstoriches story said henry 
swanson retired orange county agricultural extension agent 
theyre the biggest in florida and theyve definitely left their 
footprints on agriculture here 
last year forbes magazine listed the duda family among the 400 
richest people in america at least 60 family members share 120000 
acres in florida and a vegetable empire worth more than 550 
million the magazine said with annual sales of 186 million duda 
is one of the nations five largest vegetable growers and the 
biggest in florida duda corporate spokesman don mcallister disputed 
the magazines figures but said the companys assets are not made 
public 
in recognition of his achievements in agriculture john duda 
received an honorary doctor of agriculture service degree from the 
university of central florida in 1982 three years later he was 
installed as a member of floridas agriculture hall of fame 
the duda family has not been without controversy 
environmentalists have complained that the dudas polluted lake 
apopka by dumping millions of gallons of polluted water into the 
lake from their farming operations the state is now working to 
clean up the lake and stop the discharge of water from farmland 
