the rightwing likud bloc and the leftleaning 
labor party settled their remaining differences monday and agreed to 
join in a coalition government officials from both parties said 
the agreement came after seven weeks of haggling following 
indecisive parliamentary elections nov 1 that gave neither likud 
nor labor israels two main political blocs a clear mandate to 
govern the country 
the agreement which has not yet been signed would severely 
reduce the influence in a new government of the small religious and 
rightwing parties who had been negotiating with likuds prime 
minister yitzhak shamir to form a coalition 
during the long negotiations the religious parties had wrested 
concessions from likud that disturbed many israelis who feared their 
