<TEXT>
a federal appeals court has reversed the last 
of three disciplinary suspensions against the presidents of federal 
employee unions for actively supporting democrat walter mondale in 
the 1984 presidential campaign 
the ruling by the second circuit us court of appeals in new 
york vacates charges brought in 1985 by the merit systems protection 
board against vincent r sombrotto president of the national 
association of letter carriers and moe biller president of the 
american postal workers union 
after a series of hearings the board in 1987 ordered sombrotto 
biller and kenneth blaylock former president of the american 
federation of government employees suspended from their government 
jobs for 60 days under the 1939 hatch act the three men already had 
been on leave from their jobs at the time of the boards ruling 
blaylocks suspension was overturned in august by the 11th 
circuit us court of appeals in atlanta 
the 1939 law aimed at protecting public employees from 
machine or coercion politics forbids government workers from 
taking an active part in political management or political 
campaigns 
the charges were brought after all three union presidents urged 
their members through union magazines and newspapers to support 
mondale and oppose president reagan in the 1984 election 
sombrotto and biller also urged the respective 310000 and 
350000 members of their organizations to contribute to union 
political action committees 
in the ruling issued last friday and made public monday a 
threejudge appeals court panel said the merit systems protection 
board failed to show that biller and sombrotto had acted in 
concert with the democratic party or the mondale campaign 
organization 
it is not enough that the federal employee and the candidate 
pursue the same political goals independently the court said in 
the 26page ruling the two must work in tandem or be linked 
together for there to be a violation of the hatch act 
biller and sombrotto while holding various union offices have 
been on leave from their jobs with the postal service since 1959 and 
1971 respectively 
</TEXT>
