<TEXT>
at least 650000 children died needlessly 
last year partly as a result of the economic crisis in africa latin 
america and the caribbean the united nations childrens fund said 
in its annual report 
crushing debt has forced many developing nations to cut social 
spending overshadowing the progress most nations made in the last 
decade in fostering better health and education for children and 
their parents said unicef executive director james p grant in his 
annual report the state of the worlds children 
by far the heaviest consequences are being borne by children 
said grant 
throughout most of africa and much of latin america average 
incomes have fallen by 1025 percent in the 1980s he said 
in the 37 poorest nations spending per head on health has been 
reduced by 50 percent and on education by 25 percent over the last 
few years he added 
in many of the countries for which figures are available child 
malnutrition is on the increase the report says 
ten deeply indebted latin american and caribbean nations and six 
in africa have experienced a slowing down in the reduction of 
mortality in children under age 5 in 198087 compared with results 
in 197080 
the nations are argentina brazil chile costa rica cuba 
ecuador haiti jamaica mexico panama benin botswana liberia 
madagascar nigeria and togo according to tony hewett the deputy 
director of unicefs information division 
for these 16 countries alone the number of child deaths in the 
last 12 months is approximately 650000 more than would have been 
the case if the 197080 rate of decline in underfive mortality had 
continued said grant 
the majority of these deaths approximately 400000 in africa 
and the remainder in latin america could therefore be said to be 
related to the slowing down or reversal of the development process 
during the 1980s which is a result of unprecedented borrowing 
rising interest rates falling commodity prices inadequate 
investment of borrowed funds and the demoestic and international 
management of the resulting debt crisis said grant 
grant did not include nations convulsed by war or civil strife 
such as angola chad ethiopia and mozambique in order to limit his 
estimate of 650000 annual deaths to strictly economic problems 
the unicef report notes the developing world is now 
transferring 20 billion a year more to the rich nations than it 
receives in new aid and loans 
unicef joins the general assembly and the un conference on 
trade and development in calling for an economic marshall plan 
providing more development aid to the developing world and writing 
off the debts of some of the most deeply indebted nations 
the impact of the economic crisis tends to cloud the achievements 
of governments and unicef which are saving the lives of at least 
25 million children yearly the report says 
vaccines are now saving the lives of about 15 million children 
each year in the developing world grant notes 
at the beginning of the 1980s less than 5 percent of the third 
worlds children were immunized and diseases such as whooping 
cough measles and tetanus killed up to 5 million children annually 
his report says 
now more than half the developing worlds children are immunized 
and many nations are approaching unicefs goal of 85 percent 
immunization by 1990 
china with onesixth of the worlds children is believed to 
have just achieved 85 percent immunization india home of 20 
percent of the worlds infants is now past the 60 percent mark the 
report says 
botswana cuba egypt gambia iraq jordan oman rwanda saudi 
arabia and tanzania have almost reached the 85 percent immunization 
target and algeria brazil kenya mexico morocco pakistan and 
turkey are on track to reach 8090 percent coverage by 1990 it says 
a new goal is the immunization of pregnant women against tetanus 
which extends protection to their newborns said the report only 25 
percent of pregnant woman are now immunized and tetanus kills over 
800000 infants yearly 
in 1980 the world health organization launched a campaign to 
reduce the death rate from dehydration caused by diarrhea then 
claiming 4 million children annually 
by promoting the use of inexpensive oral rehydration salts a 
simple method for preventing almost all dehydration deaths 112 
nations now are saving the lives of 750000 to 1 million children 
annually the report says 
an expanded education campaign is now needed to teach more 
parents in developing nations about the technique the report says 
currently onefourth of afflicted children receive rehydration 
therapy and 60 percent of the worlds children under age 5 have 
access to a source of oral rehydration therapy 
</TEXT>
