consumer reports 
the viralizer is being marketed in fullpage newspaper 
advertisements as the hottest thing in cold and allergy 
treatments but consumer reports charged in its january issue that 
the device does not relieve cold symptoms and may be harmful to 
delicate nasal tissues which it said could be dried out and damaged 
by excessive heat from the machine 
robert krauser president of viral response systems inc of 
greenwich conn which manufactures the device countered the 
only thing in the story thats true is that they quote the ad 
properly where we say its the most effective relief you will ever 
receive or your money back 
other than that it was malicious defamatory and inaccurate 
krauser said in a telephone interview monday 
he cited a study by the james n gamble institute of medical 
research in cincinnati that strongly suggests the viralizer 
relieves headaches runny noses and congestion and helps prevent ear 
infections stemming from colds 
but consumer reports said the study which was paid for by viral 
systems tested the device on only 22 people and would not merit 
publication in a medical journal 
krauser said the study used 37 people and confirmed earlier 
studies involving more than 150 people 
consumer reports also cited a june letter from the us food and 
drug administration charging viral response systems with making 
claims that were false and misleading or otherwise contrary to 
fact 
krauser said those charges referred to claims made for the 
medication in the spray used in the viralizer and said labeling and 
packaging for the product was changed in response to the complaint 
krauser said the viralizer which sells for about 35 has been 
sold since january 1987 and that the companys 1988 sales will be 
about 25 million 
he said 70000 viralizers were sold in 1987 and of 2000 
consumer response cards returned to the company 250 were from 
customers who said they were not helped by the device refunds were 
offered to all 250 customers and 89 of them accepted the offer he 
said 
