<TEXT>
blobs of molten metal created where 
earths core meets the overlying rock may explain why the magnetic 
north pole wanders by about one degree every decade a laboratory 
experiment suggests 
unlike the geographic north pole where earths lines of 
longitude meet geographers have noted changes for at least 1200 
years in the location of the magnetic north pole which is where 
compasses point 
scientists generally believed that changes within the planets 
liquid iron core were responsible for the wandering of magnetic 
north but blobs of molten core material created in the overlying 
mantle may be at least as important according to the study by 
university of california scientists 
to simulate conditions at the coremantle boundary about 1800 
miles below earths surface they crushed samples of rock minerals 
and liquid iron between diamond anvils at pressures about a million 
times those at earths surface and used a laser to heat the samples 
to more than 5400 degrees fahrenheit 
the study found that molten iron reacts aggressively with the 
rock minerals known as perovskites which are composed of 
magnesium iron silicon and oxygen and which are thought to be the 
main material in the lower mantle 
such reactions could create blobs of ironrich metal alloys in 
the lower mantle that might deflect magnetic field lines generated 
in the core and could explain why the magnetic north pole wanders 
the scientists said 
ucberkeley geophysicist raymond jeanloz presented the study 
during the american geophysical unions fall meeting in san 
francisco 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
a synthesizer and computer can tap into 
the bodys symphony of electronic voices to let the paralyzed 
make music by moving their eyes or dancers accompany themselves 
scientists say 
biomuse would let a dancer create music directly from the play 
of muscle activity underlying the movement itself said hugh s 
lusted and r benjamin knapp of stanford universitys school of 
medicince in a research paper 
the idea of making music from the bodys electric signals isnt 
new but lusted and knapp wrote that electrodes placed on skin 
pick up many different signals simultaneously which merge to form 
a background of noise and the biomuse computer can select desired 
signals to make music 
the body is literally a symphony of electrical voices sounding 
at different frequencies and intensities they wrote by placing 
the pickup electrodes on the upper arm we can tune in to bicep 
activity 
next we instruct the processor to record the intensity of the 
electricity coming from the bicep then we tell the device to 
translate that electrical intensity to note number on the 
synthesizer keyboard such that low intensity relaxed gives low 
notes and more muscle tension produces progressively higher notes 
the slightest movement produces immediate sound from the 
synthesizer thus simply by tensing and relaxing one arm the 
musician can run notes up and down the keyboard 
it also could use other muscles brain or heart activity since 
the device can use any available nerve or muscle electricity as a 
control signal to the synthesizer a disabled person can learn to 
make music even using eye movements the scientists wrote 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
the surface layer of lowsalt oxygenrich 
water that supports abundant sea life in the black sea is only 44 
percent as thick as it was 13 years ago us and turkish 
researchers say 
the organisms in the relatively fresh surface water support 
fisheries in the soviet union turkey romania and bulgaria but 
scientists do not know how the change will affect the industry or 
whether conditions will worsen 
the study sponsored by the us national science foundation and 
the turkish government included five black sea cruises by the us 
research ship knorr from april through august it found that the 
surface layer extended to a depth of only 165 feet compared with 
375 feet recorded by researchers in 1975 
university of washington oceanographer james murray who 
presented the study to the american geophysical union in december 
speculated that the change may be due to dams on soviet rivers he 
said the dams already divert up to 50 percent of the water in some 
soviet rivers keeping the fresh water from the black sea but he 
said natural variations also may be responsible 
