<TEXT>
if a time machine could transport the leveraged 
buyout artists of 1988 back to the 19th century those in arrears 
might be clanging chains in debtors prison denounced as dangerous 
for selling pieces of paper called junk bonds that promise 
rewarding returns 
the comparison shows how the treatment of debt and its 
consequences have changed so profoundly just in a short span of 
western history economists and bankruptcy experts say 
once seen as a symbol of shame scandal weakness and failure 
owing money has been transmuted into status confidence and power 
a company taking on debt is now considered evidence that its 
strong said joseph chervin a bankruptcy lawyer at the new york 
law firm of rosenman amp colin its like a person taking on a 
credit line thats something you flex your muscles about you feel 
good about it 
the modernday attitude toward debt is even more startling when 
compared with the practices of ancient rome where creditors had the 
legal right to cut debtors bodies into pieces 
back in the old old days if you were a king or an emperor or 
some high potentate you could borrow and if you couldnt pay it 
back youd chop the head off the lender said robert kavesh an 
economics professor at new york university if you were an 
individual and you couldnt pay it back youd be a slave of sorts 
william shakespeare articulated englands taboo toward borrowed 
money with the line in hamlet neither a borrower nor lender be 
for loan oft loses both itself and friend and borrowing dulls the 
edge of husbandry 
in other words kavesh says stay out of debt 
a couple of hundred years ago defaulting even on a petty debt 
could land an english citizen farmer or shopkeeper in a state 
dungeon or on a boat to australia a onetime penal colony where 
many debtors were exiled 
up until the late 18th and early 19th centuries creditors in 
england had extraordinary control over debtors lives with the 
right to deprive them of their liberty until the debt was repaid 
historical accounts show that by the early 1800s there were eight 
debtors prisons in london alone with inmate populations ranging in 
size from less than a dozen to 600 most prisons were squalid 
filled with vermin and disease 
debtors prisons also were an important part of us history 
what is now the state of georgia was originally a debtors colony 
inhabited by violators of the socalled insolvent laws 
records on file at the new york public library show that in 1816 
nearly 2000 people of new york state were incarcerated for 
delinquent debts more than half of them under 50 each 
debtors prisons eventually were abolished a partial result of 
an industrialized society the development of a rational banking 
system and the evolution of bankruptcy laws but there are 
interesting relics of that era still on the books today bankruptcy 
lawyers say 
for example some state statutes enable creditors to seize 
property of debtors without a court proceeding in pennsylvania a 
legal provision called a concession of judgment allows a creditor to 
obtain a default judgment even if theres no default 
thats certainly a right that goes back to the days of debtors 
prison said neal d colton a creditors rights attorney at the 
philadelphia law firm of dechert price amp rhoads 
others say the symbolic burning of a mortgage is a throwback to 
the days when the yoke of debt could be joyfully discarded the 
shame of owing money forgotten but even that rite has changed in 
the era of borrowing to the hilt 
nowadays what you find is the burning of the mortgage instead 
of liberation is an invitation to refinance again said kavesh 
its an amazing turnabout 
on a larger scale wall street giants such as drexel burnham 
lambert inc and shearson lehman hutton inc pride themselves on 
their ability to aggressively borrow billions of dollars for 
takeovers through the sale of highyield junk bond debt 
securities it remains to be seen how much of this debt will be 
repaid though since most junkbond issues havent matured yet 
for 2000 years debt was condemned by philosophers said 
james grant editor of grants interest rate observer and a 
prominent critic of the 1988 debtfinanced takeover binge 
suddenly its not only a stigma but according to drexel burnham 
lambert youre an idiot if youre not in debt 
</TEXT>
