<TEXT>
employees at a governmentowned 
uraniumprocessing plant returned to work today for the first time 
since a 10week strike halted production of a material critical to 
nuclear weapons 
about 400 workers were asked to report at 8 am after union 
members voted by a 31 ratio saturday to approve a partial contract 
settlement with the westinghouse materials co of ohio which 
operates the plant 18 miles north of cincinnati 
workers were taken by bus to a movie theater to attend seminars 
to teach them how to handle among other things leaks of lowlevel 
radioactive materials said plant spokesman bob walker he said 
production would resume after the seminars probably in several days 
they have to go through a daylong orientation meeting for 
retraining and safety walker said 
we have had some problems with radioactive materials outside 
their containment said pete kelley another plant spokesman 
the seminars were scheduled to satisfy workers complaints about 
safety at the plant kelley said the key issues in the strike 
however were fringe benefits and retirement programs 
the plant formally known as the feed materials production 
center is the only one of 17 federal nuclear weapons facilities 
that processes uranium other plants use uranium supplies have been 
partly depleted since the strike began oct 7 kelley said 
during the strike 250 fernald workers received layoff notices as 
a result of diminished production demands the plant also became 
embroiled in controversy when the us energy department admitted 
that radioactive material had leaked into the environment during the 
plants three decades of operation 
the department has pledged to clean up the plant although recent 
reports indicate the department is considering closing it 
westinghouse materials president bruce boswell estimated a full 
cleanup would take nine to 15 years 
i think you could walk on it without rubber shoe covers 
without putting on a smock and worrying about touching things 
boswell told the cincinnati enquirer in an interview published 
sunday but ill be long dead and gone before the need to keep 
monitoring the site is over 
residents near the plant recently filed a 300 million federal 
classaction lawsuit claiming radioactive waste emitted by fernald 
has harmed their health and property 
the lawsuit names the plants previous operator national lead of 
ohio inc and its parent company national lead industries as 
defendants 
westinghouse which took over the plants operation jan 1 
1986 is not named as a defendant 
the labor agreement approved by members of 14 unions represented 
by the fernald atomic trades and labor council provides for no pay 
increase but allows the approximately 400 workers who were not laid 
off to return to work and pursue up to 4000 safety and health 
grievances 
previously westinghouse had offered to pay workers 150 each to 
drop their grievances 
the agreement also provides for 1600 to be paid to each worker 
during the threeyear life of the contract a new health insurance 
program and the right of the unions to review but not reject the 
hiring of subcontractors at the plant 
</TEXT>
