<DOCNO> AP881219-0299 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
first bank system inc will lose about 300 
million in its current fiscal year largely because it will book a 
500 million loss on the sale of a securities portfolio the bank 
holding company announced monday 
the bank will sell about 46 billion of its 75 billion 
investment securities portfolio because interest rates have risen on 
the money the bank borrowed to buy the securities said dick 
schoenke first bank vice chairman 
schoenke said the loss would not prompt the company to cut back 
on employment or on its branch system 
first bank is one of the nations 50 biggest bank holding 
companies and is minnesotas largest banking concern 
first banks expected 300 million net loss for the year would 
follow profits of 496 million in 1987 and 2029 million in 1986 
when the securities sales are completed in the first quarter of 
1989 total assets of first bank system will be approximately 23 
billion down from the current 283 billion ankeny said 
most of the securities to be sold are government bonds many of 
which were purchased during the third quarter of fiscal 1986 the 
46 billion portfolio is earning about 693 percent interest 
nearly as much interest as the bank is paying on the 41 billion it 
borrowed to buy the bonds and other securities schoenke said 
interest on the shortterm loans the bank took out to buy the 
securities was increasing threatening to surpass the amount of 
interest the bank is earning on the securities schoenke said 
by selling the securities before they reach maturity the bank is 
losing the 500 million of equity it used to purchase them schoenke 
said 
we decided to take this action because the anticipated economic 
costs risks and other implications associated with the portfolio 
hedging strategy could not be justified said dh ankeny jr 
chairman of first bank in doing so we have substantially reduced 
our risk profile and helped position the company for improved 
profitability 
the action has been reviewed by the federal reserve system and 
the office of the comptroller of the currency even accounting for 
the sales first bank still will exceed minimum regulatory levels 
for liquidity ankeny said 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

