<DOCNO> AP881219-0300 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
a federal judge ruled monday against security 
pacific national bank and the us comptroller of the currency in a 
dispute with securities dealers over the banks sale of 
mortgagebacked securities 
us district judge kevin duffy in new york ruling in a suit by 
the securities dealers association rejected the comptrollers 
decision to allow the bank to sell mortgagebacked securities backed 
by its own mortgage loans 
bank spokeswoman martha goldstein said security pacific the main 
unit of the nations sixthlargest bank holding company was 
considering an appeal she didnt know if the decision would force 
the bank to stop selling mortgagebacked securities pending appeal 
duffy ruled that the banks sale of such securities would violate 
the glasssteagall act depressionera legislation that among other 
things limits the rights of banks to enter the securities business 
the associations suit is against the comptroller and security 
pacific intervened on behalf of the defendant 
the dispute centers on the decadeold practice of banks and 
savings and loans to sell packages of mortgages on the socalled 
secondary market rather than selling single loans 
the association maintained in its suit that banks should offer 
the mortgagebacked securities through a dealer rather than 
packaging and selling the securities themselves 
in an unrelated matter a security pacific official disclosed 
that the bank had added 100 million worth of loans on arizona real 
estate to its list of nonperforming loans in the fourth quarter 
the change is balanced by positive developments elsewhere and 
doesnt affect the banks predictions that fourthquarter earnings 
scheduled for release jan 17 will show an increase over the third 
quarter said the official senior vice president jay gould 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

