<DOCNO> AP881219-0301 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
horton homes inc said monday it had fired 
87 employees who failed a recent round of drug tests slashing by 13 
percent the workforce at the mobile home manufacturer that is 
eatontons biggest employer 
the firings on friday which were precipitated by a round of drug 
tests that began last tuesday also triggered a wave of calls by 
jobseekers as word of the dismissals spread through the town of 
5000 about 60 miles southeast of atlanta 
rudy hicks the companys personnel manager said the company 
undertook the drug testing because apparent employee drug use was 
hurting production and quality 
we just cant operate with drug use hicks said theres 
too much dangerous equipment out there and it was costing us a 
fortune trying to put up with it 
most of those fired after failing drug tests friday were 
production workers although some were in management hicks said 
there is no union for production workers at the plant 
horton homes instituted a voluntary drug rehabilitation program 
three years ago hicks said but it had only limited success 
several months ago horton homes started drug screening for new 
employees and notified current workers they would be subject to drug 
testing 
hicks said the latest tests came after various complaints by 
plant employees about coworkers 
when we heard that several times in the last two or three 
weeks we just decided to go ahead and drug test he said 
ill promise you this this wasnt done without a lot of tears 
and a lot of concern theres more than just jobs here theres 
homes theres children theres christmases 
horton hired national health laboratories to carry out the 
urinalysis last tuesday testing for marijuana cocaine opiates 
amphetamines and pcp the procedure included a retest and 
verification for samples indicating drug use 
of the 87 fired 31 had participated in the companys voluntary 
drug rehabilitation program at one time or another hicks said 
horton homes officials had thought the tests would reveal a 
higher number of drug users hicks said further testing was planned 
hicks said some of the fired employees possibly could return to 
work at horton homes but that could only occur under stringent 
conditions for the employees rehabilitation 
hicks said the firings had knocked fire out of production in 
the plant friday but horton homes was swamped with job calls monday 
as news of the firings spread he said 
i had already closed applications for the rest of the year and 
now im probably going to have to open them back up hicks said 
we probably wont do anything until after christmas 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

